rotest movements across the globe - such as for equal civil status and reproductive freedom, as well as against sexualized violence - show that women's and gender rights are highly contested. Against the backdrop of a long unequal history of rights implementation, the contributors to this volume deal with the question of why and in which ways gender equality has become contested in various political contexts. Local case studies examine the relevant structural, institutional, and socio-cultural causes of the global challenges to equality. This book follows an interdisciplinary approach and unites scholars from law, linguistics, cultural studies, history, social sciences, and gender studies.  afunded by Förderung Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft (DFG) (SFB 1288)  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 4aAnti-Genderism. 4aBielefeld University Press. 4aGender Studies. 4aGender. 4aGlobal Perspectives. 4aInterdisciplinarity. 4aIntersectionality. 4aLaw. 4aPolitics. 4aPostcoloniality. 4aQueer Theory. 4aSociology of Law. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aAnti-Genderism.  aBielefeld University Press.  aGender Studies.  aGender.  aGlobal Perspectives.  aInterdisciplinarity.  aIntersectionality.  aLaw.  aPolitics.  aPostcoloniality.  aQueer Theory.  aSociology of Law.1 aBaer, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarreto, José-Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoatcă, Manuela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDurueke, Onyinyechukwu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/r